>Last we heard from you you said like March or something you lazy shit.
Well, days after my last journal entry there were multiple earthquakes, the kung flu, riots, shutdown of essential businesses. My attention was largely divided between scrambling to get things in order and fighting a battle with a resurgent wave of stress.

Recently however things have been panning out and writing has started going smoothly again. I rammed my head against BH for a while but I feel as if I've broken through and reclaimed my Muse. After getting all of this out the door I think I'll take a few days to relax, maybe practice sketching along to Bob Ross or something.
Also big thanks to Mous for the chibi art

Hopefully back on the ball this time

>rant
Yes, it was. I see your points, but they're getting a little lost in your anger. In your opening paragraph you dwell on the issue of comedy heavily implying it compromises the show by its presence, before praising Orville for its attempt at the Trek mindset and chiding those who dismiss it for comedy in the third. The nature of the main ensemble in TNG is heavily influenced by the nature of their duties and hierarchies of their rank, while the central group in the episode are largely peers, with no "dry technical insight in what these people's jobs were", so the only meaningful comparison is that they're both groups of characters on board ships - which is an incredibly shallow connection and one that is held by literally every major Star Trek installment.

You're also latching on to the death of Sito too hard. It was originally planned as more ambiguous, and there were nebulous plans to bring the character back at a couple of points; while I think the story is much stronger for its finality, it wasn't really critical to the core of the episode. Your focus on the emotional gutpunch of the ending and its part in the episode's overall drama appears to have blinded you to the actual purpose of the episode and the writer-stated reason for its existence: to be a look at the little people, and to explore their relationships away from the seat of command. That was the stuff that happened in the middle of the episode. The "hard-hitting" bit and the framing as a coming-of-age tale was an accessory to the main goal. The conversations, Lavelle's awkwardness, Taurik's snark were your vaunted character driven moments, not a viewscreen of debris and Picard's eulogy at the end.

I expect the new show to suck, but I'll give it a shot on the off chance. You have decided it must be shit, and it no doubt will be to you as you rage over every detail that you can interpret as validating your preconceptions instead of actually watching with unclouded eyes.

Greentext is literally just freeverse. I did a lot of writing in greentext specifically because it allows for more control over rhythm and meter than conventional prose does with a minimum of punctuation trickery. There's a case for it being a crutch against writing well-crafted prose because of that freedom, but you should not dismiss it out of hand. Greentext is basically just a modernization of the epic poem.

I've got a prose version of Degeneracy Pressure if anyone wants to compare how they sound against each other. They're pretty similar (I wrote the prose to recapture the meter of the greentext as best I could) but it is cleaner.

It's a pretentious-sounding name, but an epic poem is just a way of arranging words on a page that happen to tell a story. A lot of them do subscribe to a meter and/or syllable standard of some kind, but there's no law that says you have to do that. >>31505867

This is why I first fell in love with greentext, and also why I've been falling out of love with it lately. Before I was used to writing in it, greentext made me a lot more to the point than I was normally. See Degeneracy Pressure for reference. Once I really got into it though, I got long-winded again. See Silver Lining. It's a double-edged sword. If you haven't tried one or the other recently though, I reccomend it. Switching is fun. Personally, I'm going to dick with standard prose for a bit.
